Donald Trump and the economy.
New York - the financial market has finally woken up, and it turns out Donald Trump is the President of the United States.
The world has endured this powerful figure's unbridled Twitter and public statements for as long as two years, and it is apparent that the question is, what has sustained this situation for so long?
On one hand, investors have been kept in suspense by Trump's thunderous warnings, but no actual rain has fallen.
As long as he implements policies such as tax cuts, deregulation, and other measures that benefit corporate departments and shareholders, they will give him the benefit of the doubt.
Many people believe that in the end, "grown-ups in the room" will rein in Trump, ensuring that government policies stay within bounds.
This assumption has been somewhat validated during Trump's first year in office, with economic growth and corporate profit expectations increasing – courtesy of the impending tax cuts and deregulation – resulting in a striking performance on the stock market.
In 2017, the US stock index rose by more than 20%.
However, in 2018, the situation took a sharp turn downward, especially in the last few months.
Although corporate profits rose by more than 20% (thanks to tax cuts), the US stock market fluctuated wildly for most of the year before plummeting sharply.
Currently, all indices are in the correction zone (i.e., below 10% decline from the recent high), with the tech stock index (such as Nasdaq), having plummeted into a bear market (down 20% or more).
Despite the increased volatility in the financial market, which reflects concerns about China, Italy, and other eurozone economies, as well as key emerging markets, the recent turmoil is ultimately due to Donald Trump.
When this year began, Donald Trump implemented reckless tax cuts, which pushed up long-term interest rates and propelled the economy, which was already close to full employment, to a peak.
It was the fear of inflation rising above the Federal Reserve's target of 2% that triggered the first wave of risk aversion in February 2018.
Following his reckless tax cuts, Donald Trump launched a trade war against China and other key US trade partners.
Concerns about the government's protectionist policies have fluctuated throughout the year, but are now reaching a new peak.
The US's recent actions towards China seem to be preparing for a comprehensive trade, economic, and geo-political Cold War.
Another concern is that Trump's other policies may lead to a stagflation effect (growth weakening while inflation increases).
Following his reckless public comments, Donald Trump has prepared to limit foreign direct investment inflows and implemented broad immigration restrictions, which would slow the growth in labor supply in a situation where labor aging and skill mismatch problems are becoming increasingly severe.
Moreover, the Trump administration has yet to unveil plans to stimulate private sector productivity or accelerate the transition to a green economy through infrastructure initiatives.
In tweets and other settings, Donald Trump has continuously lambasted corporate hiring, production, investment, and pricing practices, particularly those of tech companies, which are already facing widespread criticism and increasingly fierce competition from Chinese counterparts.
Emerging markets have also been impacted by US policies.
Fiscal stimulus and monetary policy tightening have pushed up short-term and long-term interest rates, strengthening the dollar.
As a result, emerging economies have faced capital flight and an increase in the value of dollar-denominated debt.
Emerging economies heavily reliant on exports have suffered losses due to the decline in commodity prices, and even countries with indirect trade ties with China have felt the impact of the trade war.
Even Donald Trump's oil policies have created volatility.
US reinstatement of Iran sanctions has pushed up oil prices, with the US government subsequently cancelling exemptions, threatening Saudi Arabia to boost oil production, resulting in a sharp plunge in oil prices.
Despite American consumers benefiting from low oil prices, US energy company stocks have taken a hit.
Excessive oil price volatility is detrimental to both producers and consumers, as it hampers informed investment and consumption decisions.
What's worse is that the benefits of last year's tax cuts have largely flowed to corporate departments, rather than taking the form of higher real wages adjusted for inflation to households.
This suggests that household consumption may soon slow down, further impacting the economy.
However, the main reason for the significant downturn in the US and global stock markets in the recent quarter is Donald Trump's own rhetoric and actions.
What's even worse is Donald Trump's public criticism of the Federal Reserve, which is more alarming than the heightened risk of a full-scale trade war with China (although he recently agreed to a "ceasefire" with Chinese President Xi Jinping).
Due to these early criticisms, the market became a deer caught in the headlights when the Federal Reserve correctly decided to raise interest rates this month, while also signaling a more gradual pace of rate hikes in 2019.
It is more likely that the Federal Reserve's relatively hawkish stance is a reaction to Donald Trump's criticism of it.
Facing tweets from an hostile president, Federal Reserve Chairman Jerome Powell needs to send a signal that the central bank still maintains its political independence.
But then, because Congress refused to appropriate funds for his useless Mexico border wall, Donald Trump decided to shut down part of the federal government.
This move has pushed the market into a state of quasi-panic, with reports emerging that Donald Trump is considering firing Jerome Powell as the government shutdown looms, which could potentially transform the correction into a full-blown crash.
On the eve of the Christmas holiday, US Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin was forced to issue a public statement to calm the market.
He claimed that there was no plan to fire Jerome Powell, and the US fiscal situation is good, but this exactly highlights the question of whether the situation is really good.
Recent government personnel changes within the administration, which may not necessarily impact economic decision-making, have also left the market with concerns.
White House Chief of Staff John Kelly and Defense Secretary James Mattis are set to depart, leaving Trump's cabinet with no sane voices.
The rest will be all economic nationalists and foreign policy hawks, with only Trump in the saddle.
The possibility of a multifaceted geo-political conflict with China cannot be ruled out at this point.
A new Cold War is highly likely to lead to deglobalization, disrupting global supply chains, but the technology sector will bear the brunt of it, with the recent cases of Huawei and China as clear evidence.
At the same time, it appears that Donald Trump is determined to undermine the cohesion of the European Union and NATO during a period of economic and political instability in Europe.
Special Counsel Robert Mueller's investigation into Donald Trump's 2016 presidential campaign ties to Russia has been a Damocles' sword hanging over Trump's presidency.
Donald Trump is now the Dr. Evil of the financial markets.
Like the paranoid madman in Stanley Kubrick's classic film, he is irretrievably trapped in a cycle of mutually assured economic destruction.
The market now sees this danger, with the risk of a financial crisis and global recession rising steadily.
